ce:section.ce:para:
After the photoluminescence features were clarified, it would also be interesting to employ the fluorescent signals to monitor chemical species. To evaluate the sensitivity of the fluorescent CQDs, luminescence responses were measured upon the addition of different amounts of Ce3+ (Fig. 6
                     ). It has been observed that the peak intensity at 524 nm decreased significantly in the presence of Ce3+ from 10−6 to 10−4 M, indicating that Ce3+ can effectively quench the green emission of CQDs. In particular, the fluorescence changes could be perceived clearly by naked-eye under the UV-light excitation at 365 nm. To our knowledge, the establishment of fluorescent sensing platform for cerium detection based on carbon dots has never been reported. The correlations between the quenching effects (F0/F) of the CQDs and the concentration of Ce3+ were provided. F0 or F is the luminescence intensity of CQDs at the maximum emission wavelength without or with the addition of Ce3+. Fig. 7
                      showed excellent linear equation over the concentration range of 0–100 μM by the least-squares fitting method. In terms of the calculation, the limit of detection (LOD) for Ce3+ based on CQDs was calculated to be 0.7 μM, which was obtained by the equation of LOD = 3SD / slope. The SD is the standard deviation of the blank sample that obtained by 10 consecutive scans of the blank sample. During the above-mentioned experiments, the initial concentration of carbon dots was fixed to be 0.05 mg/mL. We also tried to use different concentrations of the carbon dots (0.01 and 0.1 mg/mL) and the results showed the higher concentration (0.1 mg/mL) gave rise to a slightly lower detection limit (0.5 μM) (Table S1).
